# Observable Framework Markdown Syntax

Markdown in Framework extends CommonMark with reactive JavaScript, HTML, grids, and cards.

## Front Matter

```yaml
---
title: My Page Title
toc: false
---
```

Common options: `title`, `toc`, `sidebar`, `theme`, `draft`

## Fenced Code Blocks

Use triple backticks with `js` to write JavaScript in markdown files.

**Expression block** (displays automatically, no semicolon):
```js
1 + 2
```

**Program block** (no display, use for declarations):
```js
const data = [1, 2, 3];
```

## Inline Expressions

Interpolate values with `${...}`:
```
The answer is ${1 + 2}.
```

## Display Function

Use `display()` in program blocks to show output:
```js
const x = Math.random();
display(x);
```

## Reactive Variables

- `width` - current width of main element (use for responsive charts)
- `now` - current time in milliseconds (updates continuously)

## Code Block Directives

- `echo` - show code alongside output: ` ```js echo `
- `run=false` - show code without running: ` ```js run=false `

## Responsive Charts

Use `resize()` for responsive content in containers:
```js
resize((width) => Plot.barX(data).plot({width}))
```

## Grids (Dashboard Layout)

```html
<div class="grid grid-cols-2">
  <div class="card">Left</div>
  <div class="card">Right</div>
</div>
```

- `grid-cols-2`, `grid-cols-3`, `grid-cols-4` - column count
- `grid-colspan-2`, `grid-rowspan-2` - span multiple cells
- Grids are automatically responsive

## Cards

```html
<div class="card">
  <h2>Card Title</h2>
  <h3>Subtitle</h3>
  ${Plot.dot(data, {x: "a", y: "b"}).plot()}
</div>
```

## Notes / Callouts

```html
<div class="note">This is a note.</div>
<div class="tip">This is a tip.</div>
<div class="warning">This is a warning.</div>
<div class="caution">This is a caution.</div>
```

## HTML in Markdown

You can write HTML directly. Surround content with blank lines to use Markdown inside HTML:

```html
<div class="card">

This is **Markdown** inside HTML!

</div>
```
